        <body>
            <div type="edition">
                <div type="textpart" subtype="chapter">
                    <ab><title><supplied reason="lost">Deuteronomy 34</supplied></title>
                        <milestone unit="line" xml:id="Deut034-P341v-L9_trl" n="9"
                            prev="ADub.III.73.005.033.trl.xml#Deut033-P341v-L9_trl" />
                        <l n="1">
                            <milestone unit="line" n="10" />
                             And Moses went up from the plains of Moab to Mount Nebo,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="11" />
                             to the top of the summit that is opposite Jericho. And
                            <milestone unit="line" n="12" />
                             the Lord showed him all the land, from Gilead,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="13" />
                             to Dan,</l>
                        <l n="2">And all the land of Naphtali,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="14" />
                             and the land of Ephraim and Manasseh, and all the
                            <milestone unit="line" n="15" />
                             land of Judah, as far as the sea to the west,</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="16" />
                        <l n="3">And the south, and the valley
                            <milestone unit="line" n="17" />
                             of the plain of Jericho, the city of palm trees, because
                            <milestone unit="line" n="18" />
                             there were many palm trees, as far as Zoar.</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="19" />
                        <l n="4">And the Lord said to him, ‘This is the
                            <milestone unit="line" n="20" />
                             land which I swore to Abraham, to Isaac, and
                            <milestone unit="line" n="21" />
                             to Jacob, saying, “I will give it to your offspring.”
                            <milestone unit="page" n="342r" />
                            <milestone unit="line" n="1" />
                             I am showing it to you, see it with your eyes, but you will not cross
                            there.’</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="2" />
                        <l n="5">And Moses, the Lord’s servant, died there in the land
                            <milestone unit="line" n="3" />
                             of Moab, according to the command of the Lord,</l>
                        <l n="6">
                            <milestone unit="line" n="4" />
                             And he buried him <seg type="commented" corresp="#Deut-034-seg001_trl"
                             />in a place called <emph>Gay</emph><anchor type="commented"
                                xml:id="Deut-034-seg001_trl" /><ref n="1" target="#Deut-034-fn1_trl"
                                type="noteAnchor" />,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="5" />
                             in the land of Moab, opposite Beth-Peor.
                            <milestone unit="line" n="6" />
                             And no man knew of his grave to this day.</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="7" />
                        <l n="7">And Moses was a hundred twenty years old
                            <milestone unit="line" n="8" />
                             when he died. The light of his eye was not dim, and
                            <milestone unit="line" n="9" />
                             the shine of his face did not fade.</l>
                        <l n="8">And the children of Israel wept
                            <milestone unit="line" n="10" />
                             for Moses in the plains of Moab thirty days.
                            <milestone unit="line" n="11" />
                             And the days of weeping, the mourning of Moses, ended.</l>
                        <milestone unit="line" n="12" />
                        <l n="9">And Joshua, son of Nun, was full
                            <milestone unit="line" n="13" />
                             of the spirit of wisdom, because Moses had reached out his hands
                            <milestone unit="line" n="14" />
                             over him with a blessing. And the children of Israel listened to him,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="15" />
                             and did as the Lord commanded
                            <milestone unit="line" n="16" />
                             Moses.</l>
                        <l n="10">And a prophet did not rise again in Israel
                            <milestone unit="line" n="17" />
                             like Moses, whom the Lord knew mind to mind:</l>
                        <l n="11">
                            <milestone unit="line" n="18" />
                             According to all the signs and the tokens
                            <milestone unit="line" n="19" />
                             that the Lord sent him to do in the land of Egypt to Pharaoh
                            <milestone unit="line" n="20" />
                             and to all his servants and to all his land,</l>
                        <l n="12">
                            <milestone unit="line" n="21" />
                             And according to all the mighty hand and according to all the great
                            <milestone unit="page" n="342v" />
                            <milestone unit="line" n="1" />
                             fear which Moses did in the sight of all Israel.
                            <milestone unit="line" n="2" />
                            <emph>Blessed be the Merciful One who offers assistance!</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="3" />
                            <emph>May the name of the great, mighty, and awesome Lord, with whom the
                                light dwells, be praised.</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="4" />
                            <emph>And He possesses the strength and the might to help me</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="5" />
                            <emph>to</emph>
                            <emph>write the peshatim of the </emph><seg type="commented"
                                corresp="#Deut-034-seg002_trl" /><emph>book of the repetition of the
                                Torah</emph><anchor type="commented" xml:id="Deut-034-seg002_trl"
                                 /><ref n="2" target="#Deut-034-fn2_trl" type="noteAnchor" />.
                            <milestone unit="line" n="6" />
                            <emph>The peshatim of all the pure commandments of the Lord were
                                completed and the eternity,</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="7" />
                            <emph>the majesty, the glory – which we praised </emph>in <seg
                                type="commented" corresp="#Deut-034-seg003_trl" /><emph>Maḥkimat
                                Peti</emph><anchor type="commented" xml:id="Deut-034-seg003_trl"
                                 /><ref n="3" target="#Deut-034-fn3_trl" type="noteAnchor" /> –
                            <milestone unit="line" n="8" />
                            <seg type="commented" corresp="#Deut-034-seg004_trl" /><emph>belongs to
                                Him and enlightens the eyes<anchor type="commented"
                                    xml:id="Deut-034-seg004_trl" /></emph><ref n="4"
                                target="#Deut-034-fn4_trl" type="noteAnchor" /><emph>. He, in his
                                mercy, will open the eyes of our heart to make us understand</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="9" />
                            <emph>the secret of the essence of all commandments, and we will be able
                                to keep and do</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="10" />
                            <emph>all</emph>
                            <emph>that is written in it</emph><ref n="5" target="#Deut-034-fn5_trl"
                                type="noteAnchor" /><emph>, according to the intention of its author
                                in order to prevent that we are turned aside,</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="11" />
                            <emph>right or left, in order not to leave the literal meaning of the
                                Scripture. And blessed</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="12" />
                            <emph>be God who showed to the people of Israel the straight way of His
                                Law</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="13" />
                            <emph>to keep us for all the days </emph>|of our life| <emph>in this
                                World, and to keep us away</emph>
                            <emph>from all trouble</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="14" />
                            <emph>so that to bring us to life on that day in the World to Come,
                                which is all lightness.</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="15" />
                            <emph>Amen! May it be God’s will speedily!</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="16" />
                            <emph>And the writing started on the first day of the </emph><seg
                                type="commented" corresp="#Deut-034-seg005_trl" /><emph>parashat
                                Shemini</emph><anchor type="commented" xml:id="Deut-034-seg005_trl"
                                 /><ref n="6" target="#Deut-034-fn6_trl" type="noteAnchor" />,
                            <milestone unit="line" n="17" />
                            <emph>on the 15th of Adar Sheni of the year 801</emph>
                            <milestone unit="page" n="343r" />
                            <milestone unit="line" n="1" />
                            <emph>by the abbreviated counting. And the writing was completed on the
                                5th day of the </emph><seg type="commented"
                                corresp="#Deut-034-seg006_trl" /><emph>parashat</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="2" />
                            <emph>Bechukotai</emph><anchor type="commented"
                                xml:id="Deut-034-seg006_trl" /><ref n="7" target="#Deut-034-fn7_trl"
                                type="noteAnchor" /><emph>, on the 23rd of the month Iyar, on the
                                33rd day of counting </emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="3" />
                            <emph>the Omer of the year mentioned above by the performer of the holy
                                enterprise, the youngest</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="4" />
                            <emph>among the God-fearing and those who respect His name – me, Simcha
                                son of my lord and my father Chananel the honourable repose of which
                                is Eden,</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="5" />
                            <emph>may he rest in peace, the prayer leader of the community, forever.
                                Here, in the holy community of Kukizów, may the Lord keep the
                                community upright forever. Selah!</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="6" />
                            <emph>Amen!</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="7" />
                            <emph>Blessed be He who </emph><seg type="commented"
                                corresp="#Deut-034-seg007_trl" /><emph>gives power to the
                                faint</emph><anchor type="commented" xml:id="Deut-034-seg007_trl"
                                 /><ref n="8" target="#Deut-034-fn8_trl" type="noteAnchor" />.
                            <milestone unit="line" n="8" />
                            <seg type="commented" corresp="#Deut-034-seg008_trl" /><emph>The earth
                                is the Lord’s and the fullness thereof,</emph>
                            <emph>the world and those who dwell therein</emph>.<anchor
                                type="commented" xml:id="Deut-034-seg008_trl" /><ref n="9"
                                target="#Deut-034-fn9_trl" type="noteAnchor" />
                            <emph>I, the young, was endowed with this</emph>
                            <supplied reason="lost">†<emph>peshat of</emph></supplied><emph>
                                Pentateuch, which I bought for my best</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="9" />
                            <emph>money for a</emph>
                            <emph>high and full price from the hands of the honourable Josef son of
                                Juhuda the honourable repose of which is Eden, may his memory be a
                                blessing, who inherited it</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="10" />
                            <emph>from his above-mentioned father, may the Lord avenge his death;
                                and up to this moment I had given the payment to his hands, up to
                                the last coin. I sign myself</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="11" />
                            <emph>with my name: Zecharia son of my master, my father Shalom, may his
                                soul rest in Eden. And the day of this purchase of mine is today,
                                the 2nd day of the parashat Bo, 28th</emph>
                            <milestone unit="line" n="12" />
                            <emph>of the moth Tevet of our year 428 by the abbreviated
                                counting.</emph></l>
                    </ab>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app>
                        <note xml:id="Deut-034-fn1_trl" type="footnote">A mistranslation based on
                            interpreting Heb. <foreign xml:lang="he" style="unicode-bidi: embed;"
                                >בַגַּיְ </foreign>
                             ‘in a valley’ as a place name.</note>
                        <note xml:id="Deut-034-fn2_trl" type="footnote">It is not the <emph>Mishneh
                                Torah</emph> of Maimonides what the copyist meant here, cf. <foreign
                                xml:lang="he" style="unicode-bidi: embed;">משנה התורה </foreign>
                             in line 5, but rather the Book of Deuteronomy; cf. also Deu
                            17:18.</note>
                        <note xml:id="Deut-034-fn3_trl" type="footnote">The work of Joseph ben
                            Abraham ha-Kohen ha-Roʾeh, Karaite philosopher and theologian, written
                            in Arabic in the first half of the 11th century; translated by Tobia ben
                            Moses ha-Abel (11th/12th century) into Hebrew under the title <foreign
                                xml:lang="he" style="unicode-bidi: embed;">מַחְכִּימַת
                                פֶּתִי</foreign>
                             , see Broydé (1904: 255–256).</note>
                        <note xml:id="Deut-034-fn4_trl" type="footnote">Uncertain
                            translation.</note>
                        <note xml:id="Deut-034-fn5_trl" type="footnote">I.e., in <emph>Maḥkimat
                                Peti</emph>.</note>
                        <note xml:id="Deut-034-fn6_trl" type="footnote">This is expressed by quoting
                            a passage read during this parashah, namely the initial fragment of Lev
                            10:11: <foreign xml:lang="he" style="unicode-bidi: embed;">וּלְהֹורֹת
                                אֶת־בְּנֵי יִשְׂרָאֵל אֵת כָּל־הַחֻקִּים </foreign>
                             ‘and you are to teach the people of Israel all the statutes’.</note>
                        <note xml:id="Deut-034-fn7_trl" type="footnote">This is expressed by quoting
                            a passage read during this parashah, namely the initial fragment of Lev
                            26:46: <foreign xml:lang="he" style="unicode-bidi: embed;">אֵלֶּה
                                הַחֻקִּים וְהַמִּשְׁפָּטִים וְהַתּוֹרֹת אֲשֶׁר נָתַן יְהוָה </foreign>
                             ‘These are the statutes and rules and laws that the Lord made’.</note>
                        <note xml:id="Deut-034-fn8_trl" type="footnote">Isaiah 40:29.</note>
                        <note xml:id="Deut-034-fn9_trl" type="footnote">Psalm 24:1.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
